releases/0/tender/title: Wickham Recreation Ground - Replacement Pavilion
releases/0/tender/description:
Wickham & Knowle Parish Council in Hampshire is pleased to invite suitably qualified and experienced companies to submit tenders on a design and build basis for the construction of a new pavilion in Wickham Recreation Ground. This project aims to replace a no-longer fit-for-purpose existing pavilion on the site. The Council wishes to receive tenders for two sizes of building:

Design 1: two changing rooms (including WC and showers) for teams and a changing room and shower for match officials. In addition, the Parish Council wishes to include a small kitchen, office space for 2 staff, small meeting room (for up to 25-30 people seated) together with storage space for chairs, tables, 2 adult sized goals and nets. There should also be external access for male and female toilets.

Design 2: two changing rooms (including WC and showers) for teams and a changing room and shower for match officials, small meeting room (for 20-30 people standing), small kitchen and storage and external toilets as per Design 1.  

Tenders are required that provide costs for the full space specifications as described above. 

The building should be modular, single storey, probably made of wood but alternative materials in keeping with the village environment would be considered. Groundworks and fitting out costs are to be included in the tender. 

Tenders may optionally submit proposals and costs for demolition and removal of the existing pavilion: the replacement may be sited on the footings of the existing pavilion, but it is not essential. Water, power and foul drainage is present at the existing pavilion. 

Tenders will be assessed against the Council's priorities which include approach and methodology, value for money, experience, health and safety and risk management, design and quality and a sustainable approach. Weightings are stated in the Council's tender documents. 

The successful Contractor should have proven experience in delivering sports pavilions, compliance with all safety and regulatory standards, relevant and sufficient insurance, financial stability and the necessary machinery. The scope of the works is in the tender documents. Tenderers should state their expected critical dates in the information submitted. All dates are to be agreed with the Parish Council.

releases/0/tender/description:
Croydon College is seeking to appoint a company to provide main contractor services at Croydon College, as per the Invitation to Tender Document that is appended to this file

The contract with the successful tenderer is intended to commence from 27 May 2024 and will be intended to conclude on 28 August 2024.

The contract will be awarded on a balance of the economically advantageous return and an assessment of the quality of information provided, as requested in the ITT.

Providers wishing to apply for this opportunity must:

The College will not consider any tenderers that fail to meet any of the criteria above.

The deadline for submitting clarification requests regarding this opportunity by email to tenders@croydon.ac.uk or JAyling@fusion-pm.co.uk is 15 May 2024, 17.00. Communications received over the telephone and to another email address will not be responded to and enquirers will be asked to resend their communications to the official tender email address above.  This is to ensure consistent advice is provided to all enquirers.

Tender submissions should be returned electronically to tenders@croydon.ac.uk and JAyling@fusion-pm.co.uk by 17.00 on 20 May 2024.  Paper submissions will not be accepted.

For full details of application instructions, acceptable format, tender requirements and the tendering process timetable, please read the tender documents attached to this notice

releases/0/tender/title: Framework for New Build Construction and Development Projects
releases/0/tender/description:
Curo wish to procure a Framework Agreement pursuant to which it is envisaged that contracts will be awarded to contractors within the Framework for the carrying out of a range of new build construction and development projects. 

The Framework Agreement will give Curo the option to "call off" projects under the Framework as and when required, either via "direct selection" of a contractor or via a "mini-competition" between the framework contractors. 

The proposed Framework Agreement will be in place for a maximum period of 4 years.

Under the Framework Agreement the following entities will have the option to call-off contracts with individual framework contractors as and when required: 
(i)	any entity within the same group of companies as Curo Places Limited from time to time (a "Curo Group Member"); 
(ii)	any entity or joint venture company that Curo Places Limited or any other Curo Group Member holds an interest in from time to time; and 
(iii)	any other Social Housing Provider in the UK, from time to time. "Social Housing Provider" for this purpose means any provider of social housing and includes, without limitation, registered housing providers, local authorities and ALMOs.  A list of the current Social Housing Providers  can be found by visiting:
 
https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/current-registered-providers-of-social-housing. 
 
Such Social Housing Providers will only be entitled to call off under the Framework Agreement if Curo consents.

Important information: This tender is being conducted through the Curo supplier portal and all documentation is only available via this portal. 

https://in-tendhost.co.uk/curo/aspx/Home

Once you have registered and expressed interest in the project, all applicable documents are normally published to the secure area within 24 hours (via clicking on `My Tenders`). If after this time you have not received your email advising the tender documents have been published to the secure area, then contact the Procurement Team by sending a message through the correspondence function. An email will be sent to the `Publish Email` address supplied at registration when the documents have been published. You will then be able to login to the secure area and download/view the tender documents. 

Submissions must be made via the web site. All documents should be uploaded to the website, then be sure to press the Red button "Submit Return" (You may need to scroll the screen down to see this button). You will then receive a receipt (print & retain a copy of this receipt and this is your confirmation of your submission). The tender status will then confirm your documents have been submitted.

System Guidance is available at:-https://in-tendhost.co.uk/curo/asp/onlinehelp.asp?help=helpoverview or via the In-tend Support Desk (number located in `Help` section)

releases/0/tender/title: HARDWARE SUPPORT AND ASSOCIATED MANUFACTURER TECHNICAL SUPPORT 2024 - Lot 1
releases/0/tender/description:
The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) has a requirement for manufacturer hardware support and technical support for key compute, storage and network hardware that forms part of the infrastructure providing the critical National HM Coastguard Emergency Service capability.

The hardware is primarily supported by a infrastructure managed service, but this service requires underpinning services for hardware replacement and manufacturer technical support.

The asset list has been split into two Lots;

Lot 1: Includes Cisco networking hardware. For these we require standard Cisco hardware and software support services to the required SLAs.

Lot 2: Includes Cisco hardware and NetApp storage arrays that are beyond the Cisco End of Support date but is still in use. It also contains our NetApp storage arrays which have a lower level of support requirement. For this Lot we require a hardware replacement service only. 

This opportunity is open to all suppliers under Lot 3d of the Crown Commercial Service's Technology Services 3 framework (RM6100).

A notice is not being published for Lot 2 because the value is below 10k.

releases/0/tender/title: Cornwall Wildlife Trust Renewables: Solar Panels, Batteries, Air Source Heat Pumps and Replacement Radiators
releases/0/tender/description:
Cornwall Wildlife Trust - one of 46 Wildlife Trusts  working across the UK - believes in a wilder future for Cornwall, where our wildlife and wild places are cherished for all to enjoy. With the support of our members, we implement projects on land and at sea, conducting campaigns and managing wild spaces to ensure nature in Cornwall thrives for future generations.
We want our nature reserves to reverberate with the joyful sounds of wildlife, to be havens in which rare species flourish and colourful plants thrive.
But we're not just concerned about the space within those boundaries - this work spills out from natures reserves into our conservation on land. We want Cornwall's hedgerows & heathlands, footpaths & farmlands, wildflower meadows & woodlands to burst with wildlife. We want to ensure badgers are vaccinated, to help beavers create new habitats, to make a hole for every hedgehog, and to see choughs remain on our cliffs as well as our crest.
Beyond those cliffs lies the ocean, where our marine conservation work at sea is equally urgent. We'd love our waters to be full of vibrant and extraordinary marine life, to provide safety for seals and dolphins to play, to ensure St. Piran's crabs make a permanent home on these shores, and to re-establish sea grass beds which trap carbon and tackle the climate crisis.
And we're also interested in people. We want to make sure Cornwall's wildlife and wild places remain a constant source of wonder and wellbeing for everyone. We'd love to see one in four people taking action for nature in Cornwall, in all sorts of ways - whether by petitioning the government to conserve 30% of land and sea by 2030, creating a wildlife pond in their garden, or volunteering on one of our many projects.
Nature in Cornwall is declining and needs our help. We're working to create a Cornwall where nature thrives
This commission is part of the Cornwall Wildlife's Carbon Reduction Plan to meet its ambitions to be Carbon Neutral.
Supply ASHP and replacement radiators to three buildings: ERCCIS (Environmental Records Centre for Cornwall and Isles of Scilly), Five Acres, Two Burrows and PV solar to the fourth buildings the Barn all collocated at Allet, Truro, Cornwall, TR4 9DJ.
The purchase of this system is part of a grant funded application process and therefore procurement will be subject to grant approval of the project. We will assess tenders received on a Most Economically Advantageous Tender.

releases/0/tender/description:
Project Summary

The council has received planning permission, subject to conditions, to demolish and remove the existing storage shed and container and replace this with a new construction in an adjacent location.

The council wishes to achieve value for money for its parishioners and hence is flexible with respect to the detailed design and specification of the new construction.
Your proposal should be in accordance with all elements of the permission and the risk assessment, Tree Protection and Arboricultural Method Statement. 

Pre-Construction Preparation

Please detail the costs for any items of preparation, to meet any conditions or regulatory matters that are required but not yet, in your opinion, satisfied for the project to go ahead to construction.

Building Specification

The proposed building specifications must meet the basic design and requirements set out in the planning permission. The Council will not consider applications that in not in accordance with the permission and the conditions therein.

Please supply a proposed design and the specifications for the building and any foundation, and a fixed price quotation for the supply and construction of the new building and its foundation. If any elements of the project cannot be fixed in price, please contact the Council in advance of submitting the tender.

Security

Please indicate how the building would be secured.

Life of the new building

Please include an estimated life-span for the building, and also all applicable warranties provided for the building and any specific elements.

Timeline and payment terms for the project

Please include an estimated timeline for the construction of the building to completion and the required payment terms.

Demolition and removal

Transfer of equipment

Following the completion of the new construction, the Council will arrange for equipment to be transferred to the new building, prior to demolition of the old building. A time limit for this transfer should be indicated in your proposal, if applicable.

Demolition and Removal

Please include a quotation for the demolition and removal of the existing building and the container. The site should be left clear of any made-made material. Please detail how the existing elements would be disposed of.

Timeline and payment terms for the project

Please include an estimated timeline for the demolition and removal of the building and container and the required payment terms.

If you are interested in tendering, please email clerk@littlemarlowparishcouncil.org.uk requesting an Intention to Tender form which needs to be returned to Little Marlow Parish Council by 2nd May 2024 by email or post.

releases/0/tender/description:
To provide Play Area Equipment and associated safety surfaces:
	a basketball net, goal and side panel, with optional cricket wicket/targets, including wet pour base and markings, OR, a standalone basketball net with wet pour base and markings; 
	an inclusive wheelchair seesaw suitable for all or a similar piece;
	interactive play panels suitable for all, such as four in a row, tic tac toe (subject to cost it may be possible to have 3 or 4 panels); 
	an additional piece of outdoor gym equipment to complement the existing outdoor gym equipment, e.g. dip bars; and,
	a 20m zip wire/cable way.

Budget for this project is 44,999.02, funded from Section 106 developer contributions.  There is no additional funding available.  Subject to the tender submissions and costs, it may not be possible to install all the proposed items within the budget, if this is the case, the Town Council will select its preferred items.  Please note if the S106 funds are not released to Burgess Hill Town Council, then the project will not go-ahead.

You are asked to provide guidance regarding the suitability of the proposed items and best value for money.

Ideally wet pour safety surfacing would form part of this contract but the Council is open to other alternatives of surfacing, however it must be easy to maintain.

Equipment and installation must comply with EN1176 and EN957.

The equipment must be low maintenance, vandal resistant and able to withstand heavy wear.  To provide the Town Council with details on how to maintain the new play, kickabout and outdoor gym equipment to ensure the equipment meets health & safety standards.

Any excavated material will be removed from the site by the contractor and the cost must be included in the quotation.  Materials must be disposed of in accordance with Local Authority regulations.

Any surfaces or features disturbed during the works must be re-instated at the contractors cost prior to handover.

The play area will remain open to the public during the works so the contractor will need to secure the area during construction and ensure that the works are left in a safe condition at the end of each working day, and take all reasonable precautions to ensure that members of the public are excluded from the works at all times.

releases/0/tender/title: CP2513-24 Restoring Stover Park Project: Partial Restoration of The Serpentine Lake - Contractor Role
releases/0/tender/description:
Devon County Council has received a grant from the National Lottery Heritage Fund (NLHF) to deliver the Restoring Stover Park Project that will completely overhaul Stover Park's valued and at-risk heritage and engage audiences who may not normally visit the Park.

The project team were recruited in March 2023, and work has now begun on the Delivery Phase, which will run from March 2023 to March 2026.

The Restoring Stover Park Project has multiple strands: upgrading the visitor centre, building a community workshop, improving the car park, desilting Stover Lake, partially restoring the Serpentine Lake, creating two new access paths, repairing the Gatehouse, installing a range of interpretation around the site, and delivering a 3-year activity programme to engage a wide range of audiences in the Park and wider environment.

To achieve this project a range of specialist contractors will be appointed over the 3 years.

This piece of work - The Restoring Stover Park Project seeks to re-instate an approximate 300m section of the former 18th Century Serpentine Lake in Stover Country Park, between the Serpentine Bridge and the Liverton Brook to the west.

releases/0/tender/title: Unlocking Space for Dual Use  Request for Information
releases/0/tender/description:
The UK Space Agency plays a major role in delivering the government's National Space Strategy.

The Government has committed in the National Space Strategy and Defence Space Strategy to a cross-departmental approach on Dual Use technology. It has also committed to identifying new opportunities for Dual Use and to embed the concept within defence capability management. To meet these commitments and to support the catalysing investment value proposition Dual Use has been identified as a priority for the UK Space Agency, promoting the development of and investment into space capabilities which can be used in the civil - defence dual use contexts by both the private and public sector. 

The UK Space Agency is in the process of scoping the Unlocking Space for Dual Use project to support this priority, and this Request for Information (RFI) will inform the project development. This RFI is directed at organisations developing technologies and capabilities that can be or are already used for both civilian and defence applications, and it has the objective of collating information on best practice on Dual Use initiatives as well as areas of improvement and potential barriers that might prevent their success in the space sector.

This RFI will help guide UK Space Agency's interaction with potential and existing Dual Use companies. We therefore welcome your responses, and we look forward to your valuable insights. Our team is grateful in advance for the time and effort taken in replying to this Request for Information. 

The deadline for responses is close of play (5pm), 27th of May 2024.  Submissions of the completed questionnaire should be sent as either a Microsoft Word or PDF (Portable Document Format) to: commercial@ukspaceagency.gov.uk with "Unlocking Space for Dual Use RFI" as the subject line.

releases/0/tender/title: 2223-33-FDR-LJ Signage
releases/0/tender/description:
Sheffield Hallam University requires signage suppliers to support our needs in relation to ongoing signage maintenance and replacement, the design, manufacture and fitting of new signage, large scale external signage, small internal signs and temporary signage, site surveys and resulting recommendations and signage removal and disposal.
All aspects of signage quality and the service provided are important to us. However we would also like to develop excellent and ever-improving collaborative relationships with the successful suppliers to support the dynamic needs of the University estate.
It is our intention, should we receive tenders of sufficient standard and acceptable cost, to award to multiple suppliers (no more than 2), to create a 4 year framework agreement with the successful supplier(s).
The design, manufacture and provision of internal and external signage, in line with the specific requirements of the University. These requirements can range from a 4m high external sign made from aluminium, mounted on the side of a multi-storey building, through to a very small, simple waymarking sign. Temporary signage is sometimes also required - this would usually be plastic or foamex. 
The quality of the signs, in line with our specific requirements and Sheffield Hallam University artwork is of utmost importance to us. We would never agree to accept or install signage that did not meet our quality standards.
However, the service aspects of this contract are also of utmost importance. These include speed of service, flexibility to react to urgent jobs, the ability to carry out site surveys and one-off site visits and generally the establishment of an excellent close working relationship with the University.
We also require good value for money.
Tender documents and instructions about how to apply are available at https://in-tendhost.co.uk/sheffieldhallamuniversity

releases/0/tender/title: Rainbow Programme Secure O365
releases/0/tender/description:
The Rainbow programme will define a new operating model for NS&I and is a critical priority for the business in order to prepare for, and deliver, the outsourced model post 2025.

A secure document management and collaboration platform, entirely separate from the Atos-supported IT infrastructure, is required to facilitate Rainbow programme work. A solution separate from the Atos infrastructure is essential to avoid any potential conflict of interest related to the procurement activity.

A secure cloud-hosted Microsoft Office 365 solution is  the most effective fit to NS&I's operational requirements and is what has been utilised since the start of the transformation programme. As the Rainbow programme's timescales have been stretched, the provision of this service by the incumbent is still required and so a new contract has been direct awarded for 12 months.

releases/0/tender/description:
We ran this competition using the 'open procedure.The procurement was conducted under the Light Touch Regime ('LTR') therefore was subject to limited regulation and conducted in accordance with regulations 74 to 76 PCR 2015. Crown Commercial Service (CCS) sought to establish a Framework Contract to support delivery of learning and development.on behalf of the Minister for the Cabinet Office. The Framework Agreement is available for use by UK public sector bodies as described in the customer list. The framework consists of the following lots: Lot 3 - Combined Lot 1 and Lot 2 Lot 6 - Combined Lot 4 and Lot 5 Suppliers will be required to provide the deliverables (goods and services) set out in the Specification.

Additional information: Notice of modifications to CCS' Learning and Development Framework (RM6145) procured pursuant to Contract Notice 2020/S 127-312150 ("the Framework"):
(i) The estimated values of the two lots under the Framework have been increased
as follows:
 Lot 3 has increased from 170,000,000.00 to 255,000,000.00 (ex VAT)
 Lot 6 has increased from 145,000,000.00 to 217,500,000.00 (ex VAT):
and

(ii) The Framework term has been extended by 3 months and the Framework will now expire on 16 July 2024.

No other modifications will be made to the Framework.
CCS' view is that the modifications above were permitted pursuant to Regulation 72(1)(b) of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (PCR).
Regulation 72(1)(b) provides that a modification is permitted in the following case:
for additional works, services or supplies by the original contractor that have become necessary and were not included in the initial procurement, where a change of contractor-
(i)cannot be made for economic or technical reasons such as requirements of interchangeability or interoperability with existing equipment, services or installations procured under the initial procurement, and
(ii)would cause significant inconvenience or substantial duplication of costs for the contracting authority, provided that any increase in price does not exceed 50% of the value of the original
contract.
In the alternative, the extension to the Framework term by 3 months is non-substantial and therefore is permitted pursuant to Regulation 72(1)(e).
As set out above, these are permitted modifications under the PCR, but, in the event that either of the modifications are deemed not to be a permitted modification under the PCR, then this notice should be treated as providing the requisite notice of a contract award.

releases/0/tender/title: TEC Partnership - Refurbishment of the Hospitality Block
releases/0/tender/description:
This initiative aims to redevelop the Hospitality school of the Grimsby Institute, enhancing both functionality and aesthetic appeal. Key components of this initiative include optimizing the layout of the staff room to provide a more spacious and aesthetically pleasing workspace, whilst simultaneously revitalizing the Open Access area to create more inviting and dynamic atmosphere conducive to student engagement and collaboration. Furthermore, upgrades to the food stores are planned, including new racking and cold stores to ensure efficient storage solutions to meet growing demands. A hallmark of this redevelopment project is the creation of seafood school, meticulously tailored to meet the highest standards and specifications of a bespoke seafood education facility. Moreover, the restaurant's transformation, featuring a bar extension and revamped interior, aims to enhance the dining experience. In addition to these focal points, ancillary spaces, such as changing rooms and corridors, will undergo a comprehensive upgrade, wherein, the corridors would incorporate hospitality-themed designs and the changing rooms would have new locker spaces along with a paint touch up and upgraded amenities. This holistic approach underlines the Institute's commitment to creating a cutting-edge facility that inspires excellence in hospitality education and practice.
      This will be done by following the Outline scope above & Specification Document.
      
      TEC Partnership has named a number or products on the drawings/specifications based upon a technical assessment and/or previous use, however the contractor is permitted to offer an alternative if it fully matches the specified technical performance of the named product.  If proposing an alternative, an example and full technical specification will need to be provided with your submission and will be subject to approval of the Group Director of Estates.
      
      Full standards and services can be found in the specification document included in the tender pack.

Additional information: To apply for this tender please visit https://in-tendhost.co.uk/educationportal/aspx/Tenders/Current and search 'TEC Partnership' to view all current opportunities.

Growth in demand for eating disorder services has expanded since the COVID-19 pandemic. Discussions with clinicians in primary and secondary care has highlighted the need for a community pathway for adults with eating disorders across Barnsley, Doncaster and Rotherham. 
The role of the Service will be to:

releases/0/tender/title: Supported Accommodation and Floating Support Service for Young Children, Young People and Families or Parents to be
releases/0/tender/description: The City of Doncaster Council (CDC) is seeking to commission a Supported Accommodation and Floating Support service for young children, young people and families or parents to be.  The successful provider should provide a safe, supportive environment and be committed to providing a sensitive, non-judgemental, and non-oppressive service. The provider will need to clearly demonstrate a commitment to multi-agency working and provide a holistic approach to ensure successful outcomes are achieved and sustained by the family.  The supported accommodation provision for the young person is intended to be of a short-term duration (maximum of 12 months) for young parent/s over 16 years of age up to 25 years of age. It is the intention that individuals will move on where appropriate in a planned manner. To this end the provider will develop the children, young people, and family's ability to live independently. The provision will deliver a programme of support. The level of support offered will vary and will be based on the ongoing assessed needs of each family. Needs will be assessed through the completion of either a early help assessment or social care assessment.   The supported accommodation aspect of the service will consist of a core building and dispersed property consisting of a minimum of 13 two-bedroom properties located within the City of Doncaster area (to be sourced by The Provider)  The floating support aspect of the Service will provide support for a minimum of 65 families at any one time (for a maximum of 12 months in respect of each family). This includes a whole family approach support package, for those who are either leaving the supported accommodation and require ongoing support to set up and maintain their tenancy as well as those who are already living in other arrangements

releases/0/tender/title: Attribute survey in the East of North England Forest District
releases/0/tender/description:
Attribute survey plots will be established and assessed following the method based on both the Forest Mensuration handbook 2006 and the Forestry Commission Survey Handbook, 3rd edition 2007.

The method will include:
Plot navigation, numbering and size choice:
Circular plots will always be used of the same size
Marking plot centres and plot trees.
Data collection to include:
Species
Planting year
Stocking
Top Height
Original planting spacing
Open ground
Map changes

Data presentation will include:
The field form, map and AP will be stapled together and returned.
All documentation will be filled in a clear and legible way
Grid references will be supplied for all plots
All species will be recorded, the use of MC and MB is not permitted unless classified as a very minor component <10%

All calculation will be completed and recorded accurately

Remarks pertinent to each plot will be recorded

All paperwork will be returned to Forest Research, Fineshade

Any major map anomalies will be noted

Additional information: Please express your interest in this tender in order to allow us to notify you of any questions we may receive and the answers given.

Expressions of interest and/or any questions regarding this ITT should be made by email to liz.richardson@forestresearch.gov.uk no later than 14.00hrs on Thursday 23rd May 2024.

releases/0/tender/title: Leisure Management System
releases/0/tender/description:
This tender is for a leisure management system (LMS) for our Sports Centres. The University has a sports centre at its campuses in Lancaster, Carlisle and Ambleside. Our extant LMS has been in operation since 2012. 
      The University is seeking a system providing customers with an online self-service portal facilitating joining, bookings, payment administration (including direct debit management and/or recurring card payment), account management, with access to these functions via a range of devices including smartphones.  
      The new system must include a reporting tool with standard reports and dashboards. Of particular interest to us is functionality to allow us to improve customer service and improve the efficiency of our business.   
      Integration with existing University systems is important to the University. Such systems include:  
      
      Student records system (Tribal SITS) 
      
      HR system (ResourceLink) 
      
      Timetabling (Syllabus Plus) 
      
      Finance system (Agresso) 
      
      Authentication system for Single Sign On (Entra ID / Azure AD or SAML2) 
      Our preferred method for the supply of the solution is as Software as a Service, completely supported by the vendor in all respects 24x7x365 including system updates and upgrades. The solution must be PCI DSS compliant, and the vendor must hold Cyber Essentials Plus accreditation or comparable certification.

Additional information: Is a Recurrent Procurement Type? : No

releases/0/tender/description:
The University events team deliver two sets of graduation ceremonies each year, one in the traditional summer period in the third week of July which is held at The Lowry Theatre, MediaCityUK and a winter graduation event in early December, currently held at the University on our Peel Park Campus. At our Summer Graduation event there are approximately 3800 students in attendance, and our Winter Graduation event there are approximately 1500 students. The University also has a small number of overseas partners who host in-country ceremonies.

At present there are two suppliers one for the gowning and one for photography. To streamline the service and provide a simple, easy, and high-quality offer for students and their guests, the University is now inviting sufficiently experienced and qualified suppliers to tender for a package delivering both of these products/services. 

The appointed supplier will be required to provide gowning and a photography service for students and their guests as well as gowns for our Vice-Chancellor's executive team, academics, and staff volunteers at both graduation periods each year

releases/0/tender/title: Market Consultation - Community Safety Case Management Application
releases/0/tender/description:
Portsmouth City Council's (PCC) Community Safety Team would like to investigate the market of Case Management Applications specifically focussing on the management of Anti-Social Behaviour and enforcement cases. The current setup consists of multiple databases, applications & spreadsheets. There is a need to look at an integrated system that serves the needs of all the Community Safety team, and offers improved workflow and task management, together with a single, holistic view of ASB data. 
      
      We recognise the experience and innovation that suppliers can bring to these services. As such PCC would welcome your organisation's market information, which will be used to enable PCC to draw up a high-quality specification that meets the needs of local authority housing and its residents. 
      
      Attached is a questionnaire for your completion. Please complete the sections that relate to the services that you provide.
      
      Subject to the response PCC may wish to engage with you further in an informal discussion. This is purely a market consultation and is in no way an indication of the selection of your organisation or a guarantee of future work. Organisations participating in the market consultation will not have any advantage over organisations who do not participate in this process. Similarly, organisations not participating in the market consultation will not be disadvantaged.

Additional information: Portsmouth City Council plan to go out to tender for a Community Safety Case Management Application.  Prior to this we would like to consult with the market and interested providers.  Any information provided could be used to assist in drafting the final specification and tender documents.

Interested parties should logon to In-tend using the link below for further details. 

To View the documents, hover over the Tenders tab and click on current, this will then show a list. If you are interested in any of those listed, click the View Details button for further information and to express your interest.

https://in-tendhost.co.uk/portsmouthcc/

This email has been sent to you as your company has registered its interest against the Business Category relevant to this subject matter.

releases/0/tender/title: A Framework Agreement for the Provision of Independent Fostering Agency (IFA) Services
releases/0/tender/description:
This procurement invites tenders from both new applicants to The Councils' Framework for the Provision of Independent Fostering Agencies (IFA) Services, or from existing providers on this framework who wish to improve their original price offers or to apply for a place on additional lots.

The notice for the original establishment of the Framework Agreement was published on the 28th July 2021 (reference 2021/S 000-017949) and the amended publication dated 7th September 2021, reference 2021/S 000-022124) which read as follows: 

"This procurement is for the establishment of a framework agreement for the provision of independent fostering agency services across sixteen (16) local authorities that comprise the South-Central IFA Framework consortium. This ITT is to establish a Framework Agreement between Southampton City Council (on behalf of the South-Central IFA Framework consortium) and those tenderers successful in their applications to be accepted on to the framework to enable the provision of foster care placements in accordance with the terms of the framework agreement. The consortium have the following needs from independent fostering agency placements:
Foster carers for children of all ages, but particularly for older children aged 10-15 years. Foster carers who can meet higher levels of need, complexity and risk. 
Foster carers who can care for sibling groups - particularly large sibling groups.    
Foster carers who care for parent and child placements
Foster carers who can care for disabled children- especially with adapted homes. Some will have complex medical needs and some may have a limited life expectancy.    
Foster carers who are registered for only one child to meet the need for solo placements.
Foster carers who can care for Unaccompanied Asylum Seekers and with an awareness/willingness to work in partnership to meet their immediate immigration, health and educational needs.
In addition, the Councils are particularly looking for local, well-matched placements, including education provision, and with commitment to the best interests of the child.     
Enhanced fostering care placements for children and young people with higher levels of need.
The Framework is comprised of the following 4 Lots:
Lot 1 (Standard Placements 0+ Years) 
Lot 2 (Children with Disabilities)
Lot 3 (Parent and Child Placements)
Lot 4 (Enhanced Fostering  Placements)  
Providers may bid for one or more of these Lots in any combination.
This is a requirement amongst some of the consortium members for foster placements that may be located with Wales. As such providers of fostering services based in Wales in addition to those in England are welcome to tender.

Additional information: The procurement is to continue establishing a framework agreement with an initial term of four years with 18 months remaining. 

There is the option to extend the framework agreement by up to two additional twelve month periods, i.e. from 1st April 2026 - 31st March 2027 and from 1st April 2027- 31st March 2028.

releases/0/tender/title: Critical appraisal of agri-environment scheme actions for achieving biodiversity targets
releases/0/tender/description:
ABOUT THE PROJECT
The overarching objective of this work is to provide a critical appraisal of the capacity of England's new agri-environment schemes (AES) to support the achievement of long-term biodiversity targets.  The OEP intends to use this appraisal to inform its reporting on Government's progress in delivering its Environmental Improvement Plan and achieving Environment Act 2021 targets.

The critical appraisal will be achieved through delivery of the following project elements, as described further in in the Invitation to Tender: 
A.  Assess the relevance and efficacy of all actions included in Sustainable Farming Incentive and Countryside Stewardship, identifying the priority actions for achieving biodiversity targets and any evidence about their uptake and implementation.
B.  Assess the coverage of specific species and habitats - and all relevant indicators for the biodiversity targets - provided by the priority actions identified in task A.
C.  A technical report synthesising the analysis.

The detailed scope and requirements for the work, and instructions for how to submit a tender, are provided in the Invitation to Tender.

TENDERING INSTRUCTIONS
The OEP now undertakes all of its procurement through the Panacea e-procurement portal.
https://app.panacea-software.com/oep 

To obtain the Invitation to Tender, ask clarification questions, and to submit a tender you must log in to Panacea then go to this project.
Tenders will ONLY be accepted through Panacea.  Tenders submitted by any other route, including email, will not be accepted.
Ensure you allow sufficient time before the deadline to upload and submit all of your tender information and documents.  You will not be able to submit tenders late or incomplete.

If you do not have an existing Panacea supplier account, on the login page click on 'Request a new account'.  Registering on and using Panacea as a supplier to the OEP is free of charge.  If you require assistance, please contact the Panacea Helpline:
Email:  support@panacea-software.com
Telephone:  0207 976 0116

releases/0/tender/title: Indoor and Outdoor Catering and Bar Provision within Walton Hall and Gardens
releases/0/tender/description:
Warrington Borough Council is seeking to expand the catering offering for bookings and events at Walton Hall and Gardens. This will involve contracting with several catering companies in order to provide customers with greater choice. This concession opportunity includes three (3) separate procurement lots, with the Indoor Lot encompassing four (4) sublots. 
Lot 1: Indoor Lot. Catering provision within Walton Hall, Walton Golf Course, The Old Riding School and other locations, catering for a variety of events including weddings, civil ceremonies, christenings, funeral after-services and conferences. For this lot, we are seeking to contract with several caterers, each specialising in one of the following sublots: 
 
	1A) High-end dining (including canapes)
	1B) Relaxed catering (e.g. pizza, hog roast, hot and cold buffet etc.)
	1C) Afternoon tea and caf (including light snacks and children's food)
	1D) Asian and faith-friendly (including Asian food and religious/cultural dietary accommodations such as halal or kosher)
 
These categories reflect patterns of demand for the hall. It is important to note that contractors will not be restricted to only providing the cuisine category in the sublot and will be permitted to cater for any event when chosen by the customer, subject to approval from the estate team. As such, all successful indoor caterers must demonstrate wide-ranging menus with options to suit a variety of tastes, preferences and dietary practices. For this lot, there is no assurance of work, and suppliers will only provide catering services for events when specifically selected by customers. For details on responsibilities and more, please see the Specification document. 

Lot 2: Outdoor Lot. Catering provision around the gardens for events such as outdoor cinemas, theatre events and corporate functions. For this lot, we are seeking to put together a list of pre-approved suppliers in support of planned outdoor events on an invite-only basis. Consequently, there is no assurance of work and suppliers will only provide catering services for events when specifically requested by the council. For details on responsibilities and more, please see the Specification document. 
Lot 3: Bar Lot. Bar operation at events across Walton Hall and Gardens (both indoor and outdoor). For this lot, we are seeking to partner with an individual bar operator. The bar is currently licensed from 11.00am - midnight. For details on responsibilities, exclusivity and more, please see the Specification document. 
As part of this process, we are aiming to significantly expand the availability of cost-effective catering options at the estate in order to accommodate a wider variety of customer bookings. We are also seeking to increase the number of events held at Walton Hall and Gardens by contracting with caterers that will undertake their own marketing and generate business for the estate.

releases/0/tender/title: Content Management: National Trails website 2024/25
releases/0/tender/description:
Natural England requires specialist support and advice to generate new and manage existing content of the National Trails website as well as investigating and pursuing resolution to any website content or technical queries. Hosting and technical maintenance of the NT website is currently contracted out to a third party (Big Blue Door) until March 2026, but Natural England requires specialist support and advice to ensure that content shown on the existing website is relevant and accurate. This support would be provided on a call-off basis until 31st March 2025 and would cover the following areas of work in relation to the website:

-advice to Natural England and Natural Resources Wales

-analysis of any problems/issues raised by general public, service providers or National Trail Officers/trail managing authorities

-responding to and resolution of queries

-solution proposal and implementation

-content creation, proposal and management

-ensuring compliance with accessibility standards

-training on creating and managing content where required - internal and for partners

-documenting procedures and guidance

-advice relating to branding and NT logos

-technical liaison as required with third parties (including current website host)

-support for website related social media activity

We expect the supplier to have a good knowledge and understanding of this area of work - access to the outdoors and specifically the family of National Trails in England and Wales.

We expect the supplier to have experience of website content management (i.e. wordpress) and knowledge and use of google analytics.

We expect the supplier to be proficient in editing and managing content on the NT website interactive maps and has access to the necessary software and technology to undertake this work (i.e. GIS, adobe acrobat pro etc).

We expect the supplier to be available and provide core support between Monday and Thursday.

Additional information: To apply for this opportunity you must submit your quotation meeting the requirements detailed in the Request for Quotation (RFQ) attached.
Your response must be sent to danny.moores@naturalengland.org.uk by 17:00 on 03/05/2024.

If you have any clarification questions linked to this opportunity or the procurement process please submit these via email to danny.moores@naturalengland.org.uk. Please note that, unless commercially sensitive, both the question and the response will be circulated to all tenderers.

The Supply of Automotive Equipment for ATAC.
The Advanced Technology and Automotive Centre (ATAC) at the City of Wolverhampton College's campus on Wellington Road in Bilston will a new dedicated technical centre for Engineering and Motor Vehicle studies taking into account the level of growth in student numbers predicted over the next five years. The City of Wolverhampton Council has received funding from the West Midlands Combined Authority (WMCA) to build and equip the centre, including the procurement of specialist equipment for training students and apprentices to the required standards in both Engineering and Motor Vehicle,

The centre is due to open for new and existing students in time for the new academic year which will start on 02/09/2024.

This procurement will ensure that the Automotive workshops (General Mechanics, Electric Vehicle. Engine Room and Electric Vehicle Classroom) are fully equipped and commissioned and that staff are familiarised with the equipment by that date.

The estimated value for this procurement is 140,000.00 - overall value of 2 Lots.

While the Council is procuring on behalf of the college, any warranties must be transferred to the College.

releases/0/tender/title: Principal Contractor - Principal contractor - Commercial (20% VAT)
releases/0/tender/description:
For a full description along with instructions about this tender please refer to the tender pack included with this requirement. 
The proposal is to create a new, sinuous path from Victoria Walk through to the existing entrance of the History of the Rose Garden. New planting beds will then be created along this path to group the regenerated wild roses closer together and explain their history and characteristics to visitors.
The main route will be surfaced with a resin bound gravel to match that of The Great Boardwalk Borders at RBG Kew. A narrower, secondary path will wind its way through existing trees which support climbing roses within more naturalistic planting. All paths will be set on a free draining,cellular confinement system using a no dig approach adjacent to trees. Surrounding soil will be graded up to meet the levels of the new paths. The entrance to the walkway will be paved with granite setts to highlight the beginning of the Story of the Rose, starting with the Wild Rose Collection.
There are two existing in ground water points on the site that will require protection during the works. These will be retained for use with new overground soaker hoses to irrigate the new planting.

releases/0/tender/title: WCC - Haulage of Food Waste from Warwickshire County Council Collection Points
releases/0/tender/description:
Warwickshire County Council (the Council) is seeking a Supplier who will provide a collection and haulage service for separately collected Food Waste stored in containers from Collection Points in Warwickshire to the Delivery Point. 

Please note while the estimated value has been stated at 1.8
million this is a anticipated figure to allow for volumes of Food Waste
tonnage across all waste collection authorities in Warwickshire. Currently Food Waste is only collected separately by Warwick District and Stratford-on-Avon District.

The initial contract term will be for a period of 2 years.
However, the Council reserves the right to extend the contract by further periods not exceeding 30 months (2 years and 6 months) in total (30 months being the maximum available extension period) at the discretion of the Council.
This means the maximum possible Contract term is 4 years and 6 months in total. 

This section is intended as a brief overview, please ensure you read the full specification.

Warwickshire County Council is the Waste Disposal Authority and manages the Council's statutory obligation to provide treatment and disposal for municipal waste collected throughout Warwickshire by the Waste Collection Authorities and/or by Suppliers acting on behalf of these Councils.

The Waste Collection Authorities (WCAs) in Warwickshire are:
 North Warwickshire Borough Council;
 Nuneaton and Bedworth Borough Council;
 Rugby Borough Council;
 Warwick District Council; and
 Stratford-on-Avon District Council.

The Waste Collection Authorities (WCA's) listed above have a statutory obligation to arrange for the kerbside collection of waste from households in Warwickshire. 

Warwick District Council and Stratford-on-Avon District Council carry out weekly collections of separately collected Food Waste. 

Please note that there is currently no separately collected Food Waste service operating in North Warwickshire Borough Council, Nuneaton and Bedworth Borough Council and Rugby Borough Council. However, it is possible that North Warwickshire Borough Council, Nuneaton and Bedworth Borough Council and Rugby Borough Council will implement separate Food Waste collections in the near future if this is made a requirement by Government or for other reasons. If separate Food Waste collections are implemented by one or all of these waste collection authorities, the Council may require a collection and haulage service for this material. Details regarding the onboarding of these additional services are outlined
in the Invitation to Tender. These additional services will not necessarily run for the full term of the contract (maximum contract term is 4 years 6 months) or at all and will instead run on a co-terminus basis with the services for Warwick District Council and Stratford-on-Avon District Council.

Additional information: Applicants are required to answer all of the questions and return their completed response (including an associated documentation) no later than Thursday 30th May 2024, 12 noon.

releases/0/tender/description:
Trafford, Tameside Metropolitan Borough, Rochdale Borough and Bolton Councils were looking to award a 5 year contract with the option to extend for a further 5 years with breaks at Year 5 and Year 8 (5+3+2) for parking enforcement and associated services.
The Councils were looking to appoint one contractor that is committed to delivering services that reflect the current and changing needs of each authority over the lifetime of the contract.

The Councils were looking to appoint a contractor that can deliver a quality service and understands trends by monitoring service delivery against compliance levels to deliver and manage change and service needs efficiently and effectively. The contractor will be required to provide an annual review of services that reflects both on what was achieved and how improvements can be made for the following year(s), these should include reviewing any changes in technology; the use of greener travel; staffing changes and training needs; what changes to update existing equipment are required along with any innovation that could be implemented to improve service delivery or introduce efficiencies.

Following an open FTS tender procedure, the tender exercise returned 1no. bid(s) from Marston Holdings Limited (MHL). MHL passed both the selection criteria and award criteria of the tender, passed the financial standing check and, in line with most advantageous tender evaluation, determined as the Councils' preferred bidder. This award decision was subject to the mandatory standstill period.

releases/0/tender/description:
EKFB is proud to have been appointed by HS2 to deliver civil engineering works across an 80km section of the new high speed rail link between the Chiltern Tunnel and Long Itchington Wood. Our scope of the works includes 15 viaducts, 6.9km of green tunnels, 22km of road diversions, 81 bridges and around 30 million cubic metres of excavation.

      EKFB is a joint venture that brings together international, market leading expertise from four leading civil engineering and construction companies: Eiffage, Kier, Ferrovial Construction and BAM Nuttall. All four partners bring specialist expertise in the design, construction, operation, financing and maintenance of railway networks, including some of Europe's largest high speed rail projects.
      
      EKFB is committed to improving lives, communities and the engineering and construction industry by providing sustained employment opportunities and being a good neighbour, protecting the environment and the places we work. Our inclusive culture ensures that our collaborative and innovative solutions provide exceptional value for money.

The Council, through its Housing Needs Service, will carry out an initial assessment of any case where there is a complaint of harassment or illegal eviction. releases/0/tender/title: NNC RFQ for a new Water Play Installation in Sywell Country Park
releases/0/tender/description:
We are inviting quotations up to a maximum budget of 35,000 for the supply and installation of new water play features in the Filter Bed play area at Sywell Country Park in Northamptonshire. The project's aim is to increase physical activity in children and families by encouraging them to move and interact together in play environment that strongly reflects the waterworks and industrial heritage of the park. We want the water play features to be eye catching,
Show less description
unique, visually attractive and to reflect the historical industrial heritage. Your offer should provide good imaginative and active play value to help us create a play area where families with children (indicative ages 3 to 12 years) can explore the waterworks heritage through play. We are interested in designs that include log flumes, pulley systems, balance scales, pump boxes, water flow, pumping, damming and the diversion of water flow etc.

Please note we are planning to hold a contractor's question session at the park between 9.30am - 4pm on Friday 12th April 2024. Please re-book your appointment by emailing geoff.simons@northnorthants.gov.uk. We strongly urge you to attend as it will provide all bidders with a chance to view the site and talk to us about what we are looking to achieve from this project.

Should you wish to take part in the selection process please complete the attached RFQ and pricing schedule and return via email to rebecca.jenkins@northnorthants.gov.uk.
